rns across all endpoints\n\n---\n\n## PART 6: docs/modificationGuide.md\n\n### Structure Requirements:\n\n1. **Title: \"Project Modification Guide\" or \"Developer Guide\"**\n\n2. **Introduction**\n   - Explain the purpose of this guide\n   - Who should use it (developers extending the project)\n\n3. **Modification Sections**\n   - Use H2 (##) for each modification type\n   - Each section should include:\n     - What can be modified\n     - Why you might want to modify it\n     - Where to find the relevant code\n     - Step-by-step how to modify\n     - Code location references\n   - Example topics:\n     - Extending functionality\n     - Changing models/services\n     - Adding new features\n     - Customizing behavior\n     - Frontend modifications\n     - Backend modifications\n     - Database schema changes\n\n4. **Best Practices Section** (Optional)\n   - Guidelines for making modifications\n   - Testing recommendations\n   - Common pitfalls to avoid\n\n5. **Conclusion**\n   - Encourage developers to extend the project\n   - Mention how modifications improve the system\n\n---\n\n## PART 7: docs/media/ Directory\n\n### Requirements:\n\n1. **File Naming Convention**\n   - Use descriptive, lowercase names with hyphens\n   - Examples:\n     - `architecture.png` or `architecture.jpeg`\n     - `user-interface.gif`\n     - `upload-docs-1.png`\n     - `step-name-result.png`\n\n2. **Required Files**\n   - Architecture diagram (PNG/JPEG)\n   - UI demo (GIF or screenshots)\n   - Screenshots for each user guide step\n   - Any additional supporting visuals\n\n3. **Image Quality**\n   - Use clear, high-resolution images\n   - Ensure text in screenshots is readable\n   - Crop to relevant portions\n\n---\n\n## ðŸ“ WRITING STYLE GUIDELINES\n\n### Tone & Voice:\n- Professional but friendly\n- Clear and concise\n- Action-oriented for guides\n- Technical but accessible\n\n### Formatting Rules:\n1. **Bold** important terms and service names\n2. Use `code formatting` for:\n   - Commands\n   - File paths\n   - Variable names\n   - Code snippets\n   - API endpoints\n3. Use > blockquotes for important notes or warnings\n4. Use bullet points for lists\n5. Use numbered lists for sequential steps\n6. Use tables for comparing information or organizing data\n\n### Markdown Best Practices:\n- Leave blank lines before and after headings\n- Leave blank lines before and after code blocks\n- Use proper heading hierarchy (don't skip levels)\n- Use relative paths for internal links\n- Include alt text for all images\n\n### Code Block Guidelines:\n```language\n# Always specify the language for syntax highlighting\n# Use bash for shell commands\n# Use json for JSON examples\n# Use typescript/javascript/python for code\n```\n\n---\n\n## âœ… CHECKLIST FOR COMPLETE DOCUMENTATION\n\nBefore finalizing documentation, ensure:\n\n- [ ] README.md exists with all sections\n- [ ] Architecture diagram created and embedded\n- [ ] All docs/ files created\n- [ ] docs/media/ directory contains all images\n- [ ] User guide has screenshots for each step\n- [ ] Deployment guide tested step-by-step\n- [ ] API documentation includes all endpoints\n- [ ] All internal links work correctly\n- [ ] Code blocks have proper syntax highlighting\n- [ ] Table of contents auto-links work\n- [ ] File tree structure is accurate\n- [ ] Credits and license included\n- [ ] No placeholder text remains (replace [PROJECT_NAME], etc.)\n\n---\n\n## ðŸŽ¨ VISUAL ELEMENTS REQUIREMENTS\n\n### Architecture Diagram Must Include:\n- All major components/services\n- Data flow arrows\n- User interaction points\n- External services/APIs\n- Database/storage components\n- Clear labels for each component\n- Legend if needed\n\n### UI Screenshots Should Show:\n- Actual application interface\n- Real or realistic data (not Lorem Ipsum)\n- Complete views (not cut off)\n- Important UI elements highlighted if needed\n- Before/after states for actions\n- Success/error states\n\n---\n\n## ðŸ”„ DOCUMENTATION MAINTENANCE\n\n